Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Chapter 7  -  Section 7.5", "Title",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "I",
  StyleBox["n this ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  StyleBox[" notebook, you will learn how to compute eigenvalues and \
corresponding eigenvectors for a matrix using ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  StyleBox["Mathematica. ",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  StyleBox["You will use these to write the general solution to a system of \
two differential equations. The solution to the system will be plotted in the \
phase plane together with the direction field for the system.",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  "\n\n",
  StyleBox["In most cases, to adapt this code to other problems, you will \
have to change only the input shown in red. To open a cell grouping, \
double-click on the right-hand side of the double cell marker.",
    FontSize->14]
}], "Subsubtitle",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
  "Problem 6:   x' = ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      FormBox[
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {\(5\/4\), \(3\/4\)},
              {\(3\/4\), \(5\/4\)}
              }], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
  " x"
}], "Section",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Finding the Eigenvalues and Corresponding Eigenvectors for the Coefficient \
Matrix\
\>", "Subsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Using the Formulas", "Subsubsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "We can determine the eigenvalues for the coefficient matrix (A) by setting \
the determinant of (A - r I) equal to zero and solving for r. We will call \
upon the ",
  StyleBox["IdentityMatrix",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " function and also the determinant (",
  StyleBox["Det",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  ") function."
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{\(Clear[A, r, x, t]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"A", "=", 
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {
                StyleBox[\(5\/4\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[\(3\/4\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]},
              {
                StyleBox[\(3\/4\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[\(5\/4\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}
              }], ")"}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(matr = 
      A - r\ IdentityMatrix[2] // 
        Simplify\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(eigsoln = 
      Solve[Det[matr] \[Equal] 0, r]\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
Then to find the corresponding eigenvectors, we can solve the following \
system of equations. Matrix multiplication requires the use of a period, \
\".\". Without that symbol, the proper multiplication will not occur. The \
warning messages are advising you that there are more solutions.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(v1soln = 
      Solve[\((matr /. 
                r \[Rule] 
                  eigsoln[\([1, 1, 2]\)])\) . {\[Xi]1, \[Xi]2} \[Equal] {0, 
            0}, {\[Xi]1, \[Xi]2}]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(v2soln = 
      Solve[\((matr /. 
                r \[Rule] 
                  eigsoln[\([2, 1, 2]\)])\) . {\[Xi]1, \[Xi]2} \[Equal] {0, 
            0}, {\[Xi]1, \[Xi]2}]\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "From this, we can see that an eigenvector associated with the eigenvalue \
1/2 is ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      FormBox[
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {\(-1\)},
              {"1"}
              }], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
  " and an eigenvector associated with the eigenvalue 2 is ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      FormBox[
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {"1"},
              {"1"}
              }], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]]
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
  "Using ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " Built-in Commands"
}], "Subsubsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " is great at determining eigenvalues and eigenvectors. We can find each \
separately as follows."
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(Eigenvalues[A]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(Eigenvectors[A]\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
The first vector corresponds to the first value; similarly for the second.
There is also a command that gives us both together. We will express the \
result in output form and in matrix form for clarity.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(eigs = Eigensystem[A]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(eigs // MatrixForm\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth]
}, Open  ]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Solving the System of Differential Equations", "Subsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Using the Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors", "Subsubsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
We can call upon our eigensystem results and insert the appropriate values to \
form our general solution. You may ignore warnings about possible spelling \
errors.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(Clear[genlsoln, c1, c2]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(soln1 = 
        eigs[\([2, 
              1]\)]\ \[ExponentialE]\^\(eigs[\([1, 1]\)]\ t\);\)\), "\
\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(soln2 = 
        eigs[\([2, 
              2]\)]\ \[ExponentialE]\^\(eigs[\([1, 2]\)]\ t\);\)\), "\
\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(genlsoln = c1\ soln1\  + \ c2\ soln2;\)\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(genlsoln // MatrixForm\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "You can see that because the eigenvalues are positive, all solutions, \
except ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      FormBox[
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {"0"},
              {"0"}
              }], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
  " go to ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      FormBox[
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {"\[Infinity]"},
              {"\[Infinity]"}
              }], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
  " as ",
  StyleBox["t",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  "\[Rule]\[Infinity]."
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Using the DSolve Command", "Subsubsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "The ",
  StyleBox["DSolve",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " command is used to solve systems of differential equations in a manner \
similar to solving single differential equations, but ",
  "you need to use the ",
  StyleBox["Thread",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " command inside the ",
  StyleBox["DSolve",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " command i",
  "f we want to leave the system of equations in matrix form",
  ". Note that we also need the \".\" for matrix multiplication and both \
dependent variables must be called upon as functions of the independent \
variable, ",
  StyleBox["t",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  ".."
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(Clear[x1, x2, t]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(fastsoln = 
      DSolve[Thread[{\(x1'\)[t], \(x2'\)[t]} == A . {x1[t], x2[t]}], {x1[t], 
            x2[t]}, t] // FullSimplify\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
The form of the second expression looks a bit different, but upon inspection, \
you can see that both solutions agree with the earlier result arrived at \
using eigenvalues and eigenvectors.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth]
}, Open  ]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Plotting Solution Trajectories with the Direction Field and Observing the \
Eigenvectors in the Graph\
\>", "Subsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
To plot the direction field, we need to load a graphics package.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< Graphics`PlotField`\)], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
The plot of the direction field uses the right hand side of the first \
differential equation as the first input and the right hand side of the \
second differential equation as the second input. The ScaleFunction is a \
built-in option that displays the direction field well here.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"rhs1", "=", 
        RowBox[{
          RowBox[{
            StyleBox[\(5/4\),
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox[" ",
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox["x1",
              FontColor->GrayLevel[0]]}], 
          StyleBox[" ",
            FontColor->GrayLevel[0]], 
          StyleBox["+",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          StyleBox[" ",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          RowBox[{
            StyleBox[\(3/4\),
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox[" ",
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox["x2",
              FontColor->GrayLevel[0]]}]}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"rhs2", "=", 
        RowBox[{
          RowBox[{
            StyleBox[\(3/4\),
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox[" ",
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox["x1",
              FontColor->GrayLevel[0]]}], 
          StyleBox["  ",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          StyleBox["+",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          StyleBox[" ",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          RowBox[{
            StyleBox[\(5/4\),
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox[" ",
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            StyleBox["x2",
              FontColor->GrayLevel[0]]}]}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"plotvf", "=", 
        RowBox[{"PlotVectorField", "[", 
          RowBox[{\({rhs1, rhs2}\), ",", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{"x1", ",", 
                StyleBox[\(-20\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[",",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox["20",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], ",", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{"x2", ",", 
                StyleBox[\(-20\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[",",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox["20",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], 
            ",", \(ScaleFunction \[Rule] \(( .4 &)\)\), 
            ",", \(AspectRatio \[Rule] 1\)}], "]"}]}], ";"}]}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
We will call upon the general solution formulated using the eigenvalues and \
eigenvectors and evaluate that solution for a set of values of the arbitrary \
constants.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(functionarray = 
      Table[genlsoln /. {c1 \[Rule] i, c2 \[Rule] j}, {i, \(-20\), 20, 
          5}, {j, \(-20\), 20, 5}]\)], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "Now, we will use the ",
  StyleBox["ParametricPlot ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  "command to plot the solutions, but, because both of the solutions get very \
large, we will limit the window for the plot."
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"plotsoln", "=", 
        RowBox[{"ParametricPlot", "[", 
          RowBox[{\(Evaluate[functionarray[\([1]\)]]\), ",", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{"t", ",", 
                StyleBox[\(-10\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[",",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox["10",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], ",", 
            RowBox[{"PlotRange", "\[Rule]", 
              RowBox[{"{", 
                StyleBox[\({\(-20\), 20}, {\(-20\), 20}\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], "}"}]}], 
            ",", \(PlotStyle \[Rule] RGBColor[1, 0, 0]\)}], "]"}]}], 
      ";"}]], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "Now, we can plot these together. If they do not match, we have made a \
mistake. The limitation expressed in ",
  StyleBox["PlotRange",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " is necessary here as well."
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Show", "[", 
        RowBox[{"plotvf", ",", "plotsoln", ",", 
          RowBox[{"PlotRange", "\[Rule]", 
            RowBox[{
              StyleBox["{",
                FontColor->GrayLevel[0]], 
              StyleBox[\({\(-20\), 20}, {\(-20\), 20}\),
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], "}"}]}]}], "]"}], 
      ";"}]], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
Print out the above graph and draw your eigenvectors on the graph. What \
conclusions might you draw from this? Try another problem from this set and \
do the same.\
\>", "Text"]
}, Closed]]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
